}} 'Rouen' (), in northern France on the River Seine, is the capital of the
[[Upper Normandy|Haute-Normandie]] (Upper Normandy) region and the historic
capital city of Normandy. Once one of the largest and most prosperous cities of
medieval Europe , it was the seat of the Exchequer of Normandy in the Middle
Ages. It was one of the capitals of the Anglo-Norman dynasties, which ruled both
England and large parts of modern France from the 11th to the 15th centuries. It
was here that Joan of Arc was executed in 1431. People from Rouen are called
Rouennais.

The population of the metropolitan area (in French: agglomÃ©ration) at the 1999
census was 518,316, and 532,559 at the 2007 estimate. The city proper had an
estimated population of 110,276 in 2007.
